Mr. Smith is a 71-year-old African-American male with past medical history significant for chronic respiratory failure on 3 L of home oxygen, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, chronic obstructive pulmonary disease, asthma, obstructive sleep apnea on CPAP, former tobacco use, and other medical problems who presented to the Methodist South Hospital emergency department with complaints of shortness of breath. The patient reports that his symptoms have been ongoing for the past 2 weeks but worsened over the last 2 days. .
On arrival to the emergency department patient was tachycardic with a heart rate of 103. EKG showed sinus rhythm with nonspecific T wave abnormality with a rate of 95. Pertinent laboratory studies included chloride 111, glucose 135, CK5 06, RBC 4.07, hemoglobin 11.3, hematocrit 35.5, and D-dimer 1.01. Initial and repeat troponin levels were negative. Urine drug screen was positive for opiates. Chest x-ray showed emphysema and subsegmental left lower lobe atelectasis. CT thorax showed a new 1.8 cm spiculated mass to the right lung apex which was not noted on previous CT chest completed 2023-02-22 with differentials including acute infection or inflammatory process however histologic sampling was recommended as primary lung malignancy was also a primary differential consideration. Right hip x-ray and right femur x-ray were negative. The patient received nebulizer breathing treatments, intravenous antibiotics, and intravenous steroids in the emergency department.
Upon initial physician evaluation after overnight admission the patient was found to be somnolent/lethargic and not responding to commands nor questions. he was hypoxic on conventional nasal cannuli and given concern for impending respiratory failure in the setting of acute hypercapneic hypoxemic respiratory failure he was emergently intubated.
A/P:
Acute encephalopathy: etiology CO2 narcosis. CT brain negative. Intubated on 6/27 & extubated on 6/28. Patient now DNR/DNI.
Acute on chronic hypoxemic and hypercapnic respiratory failure: improved Now s/p extubation on 6/28. On prn BiPAP & while asleep.
HTN emergency: resolved
COPD exacerbation: Prednisone tapering dose. bronchodilators and inhaled corticosteroids.
Lung mass: 1.8 cm spiculation mass RUL, pulmonary following and discussed the lesion with the patient & patient does not want to persue bronch.
Diastolic CHF: not in exacerbation currently, monitoring.
Ileus: resolved
Anemia; mild chronic and stable
HLD: continue statin
OSA: C-PAP
Hyperkalemia: Sodium zirconium. Monitoring.
DVT ppx
TARGET DISCHARGE DATE:
PT/OT recommended HH vs SNF. Patient asking to go home stating he lives with his sister. Asking for HH.
Patient needs additional CHOICES hours based on his clinical conditions.
Brief hospital course:
The patient presented to methodist south hospital due to SOB in the setting of acute hypoxic and hypercapneic respiratory failure secondary to acute on chronic COPD exacerbation. he was initiallyl managed in the ER and transferred to the floors. Upon arrival to the floors and physiican evaluation he was found to be somnolent/obtunded and was emergently intubated. ABG demonstrted a severe respiratory acidosis which indicated a likely etiology of CO2 narcosis. With ventilator management his respiratory status improved and his encephalopathy resolved. he was subsequently extubated to nasal cannuli and kept on BIPAP qhs and prn. He elected at that time to be DNR and DNI. he was found to have a 1.8cm spiculated mass on the RUL but after discussion with pulmonary services the patient elected to not pursue bronchoscopy. He was evaluated with PT recommending SNF vs HH and he desired to return home with his sister. Case manager/SW arranged for choices program given his needs and he was subsequently discharged home in stable condition.

Clinical Information: Abnormal x-ray, interstitial infiltrates
Examination: CT Chest with IV Contrast, 2023-03-26 3:25 PM, CT220088306
Comparison: CT chest performed 2023-02-22, chest x-ray performed 2023-03-26
All CT scans at this facility use dose modulation, iterative reconstruction, and/or weight-based dosing when appropriate to reduce radiation dose to as low as reasonably achievable.
Findings: Helically acquired images were obtained from the thoracic inlet to the level of the diaphragm following the intravenous administration of contrast. Multiplanar reconstructions were performed and reviewed.
There is circumferential thickening at the level the vocal cords, which may be secondary to motion during the examination. Thyroid gland appears normal. The trachea is patent. Heart is normal in size. No pericardial effusion. Coronary atherosclerosis is noted. The thoracic aorta demonstrates calcific atherosclerosis without aneurysmal dilatation or dissection. The main pulmonary artery and right left pulmonary arteries are normal in caliber. No mediastinal or axillary lymphadenopathy. Extensive emphysema is noted bilaterally. There is linear atelectasis involving the lingula. There is a new spiculated mass in the right lung apex measuring 1.8 x 1.5 cm. No lobar consolidation, pleural effusion, or pneumothorax.
No acute abnormality is noted of the upper abdomen. No acute bony abnormalities are seen. Thoracic degenerative spurring is noted. Superficial soft tissues are normal.
Impression:
1. New 1.8 cm spiculated mass right lung apex, new since previous CT chest performed 2023-02-22. While it is possible that this could represent an acute infectious or inflammatory process as this is a new finding within the past month, histologic sampling would be recommended as primary lung malignancy is a primary differential consideration.
2. Emphysema.
3. Atherosclerosis with involvement of the coronary vessels.

TECHNICAL: Multiple axial images were obtained from the aortic arch to the vertex prior to and after the intravenous administration of 70 mL Isovue-370 contrast media.
All CT scans at this facility use dose modulation, iterative reconstruction, and/or weight based dosing when appropriate to reduce radiation dose to as low as reasonably achievable.
COMPARISON: CT thorax 2023-03-26
FINDINGS: Axial images obtained prior to and after the intravenous administration of contrast. 3-D postprocessed/MIPS images obtained from the axial data set.
CTA NECK: There is no stenosis of the origins of the great vessels off the aortic arch.
There is no stenosis of the common carotid arteries.
There is nonhemodynamically significant atherosclerosis of the bilateral common carotid bulbs. No focal stenotic lesion is seen.
The mid and distal cervical ICAs are patent.
The vertebral arteries are patent. There is no origin stenosis.
The patient is intubated. The endotracheal tube terminates above the carina. Incompletely visualized spiculated soft tissue density lesion in the right upper lobe which measures 1.8 x 1.2 cm. There are emphysematous changes in the lung apices.
CTA HEAD: The distal internal carotid arteries demonstrate nonhemodynamically significant atherosclerosis and are patent.
The visualized vertebrobasilar system is patent.
The proximal cerebral arteries and their visualized branch vessels are patent.
There is normal-appearing intracranial venous opacification.
The visualized paranasal sinuses and mastoid air cells are clear.
IMPRESSION:
1. Atherosclerosis of the carotid bifurcations. Otherwise normal CT angiogram of the neck. No findings seen to suggest flow-limiting stenosis per NASCET criteria.
2. Atherosclerosis of the intracranial ICAs, without stenosis. Otherwise normal CT angiogram of the head.
3. Incompletely visualized spiculated soft tissue density lesion in the right upper lobe of the lung. Please see separate recent CT thorax report. [3]
